	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Mon, Sep 10th 8:22 AM 2001</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Decent<span id=notbold>[3.13]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>Ok, I had to answer this one. Because, well, this is strategy. I have a theory for dealing with a caster/pet combo in a duel and wanted input from you. I guess this kid's taunting post is a good place to seek input.<br><br>My theory is that when dueling a caster, you should ignore pet and kill mage. Ofcourse, I know how well it would work would depend on the pet being used. Some of the pets proc not nice spells, and they get not nicer as they go up in level.<br><br>My theory is an inexperienced mage would try to root you with earthpet. Now, depending on your level, I would think debuff song would take care of that, right? Earth pets are notorious for constantly casting root rather than hitting. As long as your debuff song ready, you should be able to keep closing with the mage. All other times, you use your regen song or strength song.<br><br>Don't we eventually even get a lull song? Ofcourse, it would break on the pet as soon as you hit the mage, which would be quick because thier ac is notoriously low. No offense to mages. it's the type of "armor" you can use. <br><br>I would think the worst thing to do is to engage pet. As bad as pet procs can be, mage spells are far worse. So are enchanter spells (but I'll get to them in a moment). If mage is gone, then pet is gone. end of problem.<br><br>IMO, the worst class to have to duel against would be an Enchanter. Why?<br><br>1. Okay, Enchanter start with DoTs. Infact, it seems most of thier spells center around making you suffer...slowly. I play an enchanter and a necromancer, and I've come to the opinion that enchanters are nice necromancer. *wink* Seriously, the do both have some similar spells. It is just what they do with what they take away.<br><br>2. Mez. At lvl 4, ehcanters start mezzing. Among other nasty tricks. A level 4 enchanter could keep you mezzed until he decided what to do with you.<br><br>3. By level 8, Enchanters are stunning. And I don't mean thier beauty. Chaotic feedback is nasty because it is an all-or-nothing, and I've seen it do all far more often than nothing (I'm trying to think if I ever seen it do nothing with my enchanter). <br><br>4. By level 12, they are charming. Again, not beauty. This is, to me, what would make an Enchanter most undesirable to duel.<br><br>Picture, if you will, headstrong mage. Wants to duel a chanter.<br><br>I see one of 2 things happening.<br>1. (if it is possible, I think it is) the 'chanter charms the mage's pet. Ouch.<br><br>2. The chanter charms the mage, says /pet attack &lt;insert guard&gt;. Then chanter heads to zone, waits to hear they've won duel, and zones.<br><br>You are seeing how this is bad. While you are shrugging off the animation's taunts (assuming he is even wasting the mana, depending on lvl) he's got you dot'd, mezzed, and charmed. By that time, you're history.<br><br>My theories, ofcourse. <br><br>So this is a strategy forum. Strategize. ;)<br><br><br><br><br><br><br>&nbsp;<br>"In waking a tiger, use a very long stick." -Mao Tse-Tung. Did he go to Stonebrunt too?</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 >&nbsp;</td><td align=right valign=bottom>
